1
00:02:29,649 --> 00:02:31,241
<i>NARRATOR: Once upon a time,</i>

2
00:02:31,351 --> 00:02:33,478
<i>there was a brave little mouse</i>

3
00:02:33,553 --> 00:02:37,250
<i>who loved honor and justice</i>
<i>and always told the truth.</i>

4
00:02:37,924 --> 00:02:39,186
(CAPTAIN BARKING ORDERS)

5
00:02:51,838 --> 00:02:53,567
<i>No, that's not him.</i>

6
00:02:53,740 --> 00:02:54,764
(YAWNING)

7
00:02:55,275 --> 00:02:56,742
<i>That's a rat.</i>

8
00:02:57,076 --> 00:02:58,202
<i>And anyone who knows anything,</i>

9
00:02:58,278 --> 00:03:00,838
<i>knows there's a big difference</i>
<i>between a mouse and a rat.</i>

10
00:03:00,914 --> 00:03:01,938
Ohhh.

11
00:03:02,215 --> 00:03:05,007
<i>First of all,
rats hate the light.</i>

12
00:03:05,919 --> 00:03:07,045
(GROANS)

13
00:03:07,687 --> 00:03:10,281
<i>They spend their
lives in the darkness.</i>

14
00:03:10,623 --> 00:03:11,885
<i>They're also terrified of people,</i>

15
00:03:11,958 --> 00:03:14,085
<i>which is why they slink</i>
<i>and cower all the time.</i>

16
00:03:14,194 --> 00:03:15,218
Ooh!

17
00:03:15,562 --> 00:03:17,757
<i>And as far as telling
the truth is concerned,</i>

18
00:03:17,864 --> 00:03:20,628
<i>well, that's impossible</i>
<i>because, as everyone knows,</i>

19
00:03:20,900 --> 00:03:21,958
(CLEARS THROAT)

20
00:03:22,068 --> 00:03:23,797
<i>a rat can't talk.</i>

21
00:03:23,970 --> 00:03:25,460
Tell me that thing again, please.

22
00:03:25,939 --> 00:03:27,133
Come on.

23
00:03:27,807 --> 00:03:29,104
Just once, I promise.

24
00:03:29,209 --> 00:03:30,301
Tell me one more time,

25
00:03:30,410 --> 00:03:32,071
and I won't ask you ever again. I swear.

26
00:03:32,145 --> 00:03:33,237
(SIGHS)

27
00:03:33,313 --> 00:03:36,248
Fine. We are headed to Dor,

28
00:03:36,316 --> 00:03:39,114
one of the most
magical places in the whole world.

29
00:03:39,219 --> 00:03:40,743
No, that's not what you said before.

30
00:03:40,820 --> 00:03:43,380
You know, every place
has something special.

31
00:03:43,456 --> 00:03:45,924
And, in Dor, it's the soup!

32
00:03:46,059 --> 00:03:47,754
SAILOR: Land ho!

33
00:03:47,894 --> 00:03:49,759
(SAILORS CHEER)

34
00:03:51,965 --> 00:03:52,989
Ohhh.

35
00:03:54,167 --> 00:03:55,566
SAILOR 1: It's down below, I tell you.

36
00:03:55,635 --> 00:03:56,659
SAILOR 2: Give it a heave.

37
00:04:01,774 --> 00:04:03,241
I can see it!

38
00:04:05,678 --> 00:04:09,409
Ooh, I can smell it! I can smell it.

39
00:04:16,756 --> 00:04:19,281
ROSCURO: Oh, I can't wait
to taste the soup!

40
00:04:19,592 --> 00:04:21,082
Just stay close.

41
00:04:21,160 --> 00:04:22,422
We leave again at 6:00.

42
00:04:22,495 --> 00:04:25,328
You know, we ought to think
about staying here just a little longer.

43
00:04:25,431 --> 00:04:27,422
Don't even think about it.

44
00:04:27,700 --> 00:04:28,758
Remember Shanghai?

45
00:04:28,835 --> 00:04:30,427
Yeah, but this place is different.

46
00:04:30,837 --> 00:04:32,805
I mean, this is special.

47
00:04:35,341 --> 00:04:39,038
<i>NARRATOR: On any given day,</i>
<i>just one whiff from one of the soup shops</i>

48
00:04:39,145 --> 00:04:41,545
<i>was almost like
having a full meal.</i>

49
00:04:42,215 --> 00:04:45,150
<i>But on one very
special day every year,</i>

50
00:04:45,218 --> 00:04:48,187
<i>the kingdom of Dor</i>
<i>was magically transformed.</i>

51
00:04:48,288 --> 00:04:50,779
(CROWD CHEERING)

52
00:04:50,857 --> 00:04:52,848
<i>In Dor, Christmas was nothing.</i>

53
00:04:52,959 --> 00:04:54,517
<i>Well, they still celebrated it,</i>

54
00:04:54,627 --> 00:04:57,323
<i>but it was nothing
compared to Soup Day.</i>

55
00:05:02,368 --> 00:05:03,392
Watch it, watch it.

56
00:05:03,503 --> 00:05:05,368
Incoming potatoes!

57
00:05:05,471 --> 00:05:07,200
Hurry! Hurry! Excuse us.

58
00:05:07,307 --> 00:05:10,367
<i>Every Dorian, young and old,</i>
<i>would flock toward the castle</i>

59
00:05:10,476 --> 00:05:13,502
<i>because they knew that,
at that very moment,</i>

60
00:05:13,579 --> 00:05:16,207
<i>deep within the royal kitchens,</i>

61
00:05:16,316 --> 00:05:18,181
<i>a masterpiece was being created.</i>

62
00:05:18,251 --> 00:05:20,014
DELIVERY MAN: Potatoes coming up!

63
00:05:27,427 --> 00:05:28,485
COOK 1: Let's go!

64
00:05:28,561 --> 00:05:29,585
COOK 2: Don't forget the parsley!

65
00:05:29,896 --> 00:05:31,363
COOK 1: Make sure it's clean!

66
00:05:42,408 --> 00:05:44,569
<i>NARRATOR: Everyone knew</i>
<i>Chef Andre was a genius,</i>

67
00:05:44,677 --> 00:05:49,046
<i>but they got reminded of it</i>
<i>on the first Sunday of every spring.</i>

68
00:05:50,883 --> 00:05:53,215
<i>At exactly 12:00 noon,</i>

69
00:05:53,286 --> 00:05:56,722
<i>he would unveil that
year's royal creation.</i>

70
00:06:09,736 --> 00:06:10,862
More onions!

71
00:06:10,937 --> 00:06:11,961
More onions!

72
00:06:12,071 --> 00:06:13,095
More onions!

73
00:06:13,206 --> 00:06:14,264
More onions!

74
00:06:15,908 --> 00:06:17,876
<i>They would jam the town square,</i>

75
00:06:17,944 --> 00:06:20,242
<i>and, as the aroma began to build,</i>

76
00:06:20,313 --> 00:06:22,440
<i>so did their anticipation.</i>

77
00:06:25,084 --> 00:06:26,984
- Ohhh!
- Ow!

78
00:06:27,086 --> 00:06:28,110
Sorry.

79
00:06:28,221 --> 00:06:29,916
(TRUMPET FANFARE PLAYING)

80
00:06:29,989 --> 00:06:31,047
(CROWD CHEERING)

81
00:06:36,562 --> 00:06:37,620
Wow.

82
00:06:40,400 --> 00:06:41,458
Thank you.

83
00:06:41,567 --> 00:06:42,591
(CLEARS THROAT)

84
00:06:42,802 --> 00:06:47,637
It's my pleasure to announce
this year's royal creations

85
00:06:47,907 --> 00:06:50,205
from the kitchens of Chef Andre.

86
00:06:50,710 --> 00:06:51,972
Oh, no, no, no, no, no!

87
00:06:52,078 --> 00:06:53,545
Something is wrong.

88
00:06:53,613 --> 00:06:55,240
I need more time!

89
00:06:55,381 --> 00:06:56,609
But we're late already!

90
00:06:56,716 --> 00:06:58,308
This is not right!

91
00:07:00,453 --> 00:07:01,943
Everyone out!

92
00:07:02,388 --> 00:07:03,412
Out!

93
00:07:06,926 --> 00:07:10,555
<i>NARRATOR: Now, it's hard to</i>
<i>be a genius all by yourself.</i>

94
00:07:11,097 --> 00:07:14,897
<i>In fact, sometimes,
it takes a little help.</i>

95
00:07:38,291 --> 00:07:39,690
You changed something.

96
00:07:40,026 --> 00:07:42,119
You're crazy. I did not touch it.

97
00:07:42,195 --> 00:07:43,287
- I can smell it.
- Hmm?

98
00:07:43,362 --> 00:07:44,454
- What's this?
- What?

99
00:07:44,530 --> 00:07:46,157
- This!
- Ow! Garlic.

100
00:07:46,599 --> 00:07:47,759
- Garlic.
- Yeah, a little garlic.

101
00:07:48,367 --> 00:07:49,925
- It was already there.
- No.

102
00:07:50,002 --> 00:07:51,026
- Yes.
- No.

103
00:07:51,137 --> 00:07:52,195
- Yes.
- Not this much!

104
00:07:52,305 --> 00:07:53,329
Ow!

105
00:07:53,439 --> 00:07:54,531
You ruined my soup!

106
00:07:54,640 --> 00:07:56,039
I save your soup!

107
00:07:56,142 --> 00:08:01,136
Those people wait all year,
and you want to give them this dishwater.

108
00:08:01,881 --> 00:08:03,178
Dishwater?

109
00:08:03,282 --> 00:08:04,510
Dishwater.

110
00:08:04,617 --> 00:08:05,675
Dishwater?

111
00:08:05,785 --> 00:08:06,877
Ow! Cut it out!

112
00:08:07,019 --> 00:08:08,281
(CLAMORING)

113
00:08:09,689 --> 00:08:10,986
(CROWD CHEERING)

114
00:08:11,057 --> 00:08:12,820
And this year's soup is

115
00:08:14,861 --> 00:08:16,829
a spring tureen

116
00:08:16,896 --> 00:08:18,625
with a <i>mélange</i>
of roasted vegetables...

117
00:08:18,698 --> 00:08:19,722
Oh.

118
00:08:19,832 --> 00:08:21,561
...fresh herbs...
- Mmm!

119
00:08:21,667 --> 00:08:23,328
...and wild mushrooms.

120
00:08:23,402 --> 00:08:24,528
Oh.

121
00:08:25,204 --> 00:08:26,466
Roscuro?

122
00:08:30,643 --> 00:08:32,076
Roscuro?

123
00:08:32,712 --> 00:08:34,475
Oh. Evening.

124
00:08:38,484 --> 00:08:42,921
CHEF ANDRE: I don't have to stand here
and listen to a big talking garbage can!

125
00:08:43,089 --> 00:08:46,718
BOLDO: Ha! And I don't have
to stand here and listen to a coward!

126
00:08:47,026 --> 00:08:48,584
- Coward?
- Yes, a coward!

127
00:08:48,694 --> 00:08:50,525
- You call me coward?
- Yes!

128
00:08:50,596 --> 00:08:52,359
(SCREAMS)

129
00:08:52,932 --> 00:08:54,194
(GASPS)

130
00:08:54,600 --> 00:08:56,067
Oh, no!

131
00:09:03,943 --> 00:09:05,001
(EXCLAIMS)

132
00:09:07,513 --> 00:09:09,071
(BOLDO YELPS)

133
00:09:13,586 --> 00:09:15,076
Oh, no, no, no, no, no.

134
00:09:15,187 --> 00:09:16,745
(MUTTERING) That did it.

135
00:09:21,127 --> 00:09:22,890
- Hmm?
- Mmm.

136
00:09:23,296 --> 00:09:24,627
BOTH: Mmm!

137
00:09:24,964 --> 00:09:26,556
(CHUCKLES)

138
00:09:26,632 --> 00:09:28,862
<i>- Bellissima!</i>
- It's <i>fantastique!</i>

139
00:09:28,935 --> 00:09:31,904
Roscuro! Roscuro, where are you?

140
00:09:33,072 --> 00:09:34,596
(TRUMPET FANFARE PLAYING)

141
00:09:35,141 --> 00:09:36,267
Ohhh.

142
00:09:43,616 --> 00:09:44,878
(DRUM ROLLS)

143
00:09:48,588 --> 00:09:49,919
(ALL GASP)

144
00:09:55,494 --> 00:09:56,586
(SNIFFS)

145
00:09:56,662 --> 00:09:57,890
Whoa!

146
00:10:13,679 --> 00:10:14,805
(SNIFFS)

147
00:10:19,585 --> 00:10:20,745
<i>Voilà!</i>

148
00:10:21,020 --> 00:10:24,080
This is amazing!

149
00:10:24,323 --> 00:10:26,018
CHEF ANDRE: Wait till
Your Highness tastes it.

150
00:10:28,294 --> 00:10:29,318
Hmm?

151
00:10:41,173 --> 00:10:42,538
QUEEN: This is...

152
00:10:42,642 --> 00:10:43,666
Whoa!

153
00:10:43,776 --> 00:10:45,767
...absolutely...

154
00:10:45,845 --> 00:10:46,869
(EXCLAIMS)

155
00:10:46,979 --> 00:10:50,813
Oh, it moved! My soup moved!

156
00:10:50,983 --> 00:10:53,178
No, it isn't... It did not move.

157
00:10:53,853 --> 00:10:55,047
Oh, Your Highness.

158
00:10:55,154 --> 00:10:56,212
- Ahhh!
- Darling?

159
00:10:56,322 --> 00:10:59,314
Oh! A rat! There's a rat in my soup!

160
00:10:59,392 --> 00:11:01,019
Madam, I know that this is unfortunate.

161
00:11:01,127 --> 00:11:03,288
And I know that
while on first glance, I might...

162
00:11:03,362 --> 00:11:05,489
- A rat! In my soup!
- No. Please. Shh, shh, shh.

163
00:11:05,564 --> 00:11:07,657
- And I ate it!
- Your Highness, hold on...

164
00:11:07,733 --> 00:11:08,791
(GAGGING)

165
00:11:08,868 --> 00:11:10,665
- Uh-oh.
- She's right! It's a rat!

166
00:11:10,736 --> 00:11:11,828
(GASPS)

167
00:11:11,904 --> 00:11:13,963
- Please...
- Ahhh! It's a rat!

168
00:11:14,840 --> 00:11:17,866
Get me that rat!

169
00:11:18,210 --> 00:11:19,905
Now, I really believe
you're jumping to conclusions.

170
00:11:20,413 --> 00:11:21,903
And I'm sure that the
rats you met last time

171
00:11:22,014 --> 00:11:24,209
might have caused you
to create a stereotype,

172
00:11:24,316 --> 00:11:25,874
but... But I... But...

173
00:11:25,985 --> 00:11:28,215
It's just... I'm just...
I'm not really from around here.

174
00:11:28,320 --> 00:11:30,049
I'm... I'm from... Oh...

175
00:11:30,156 --> 00:11:31,214
Oh!

176
00:11:31,323 --> 00:11:32,756
That's very aggressive.

177
00:11:33,325 --> 00:11:34,383
GUARD: Get him!

178
00:11:34,493 --> 00:11:35,551
Kitchen...

179
00:11:35,661 --> 00:11:36,923
He's going into the kitchen!

180
00:11:39,265 --> 00:11:40,323
Oh!

181
00:11:45,237 --> 00:11:46,295
GUARD: Over there!

182
00:11:47,506 --> 00:11:49,133
Stop that rat!

183
00:11:49,909 --> 00:11:51,137
Whoa!

184
00:11:51,911 --> 00:11:52,969
GUARD: I got him!

185
00:11:53,045 --> 00:11:54,137
Uh-oh.

186
00:12:01,053 --> 00:12:03,715
He's going near the soup!

187
00:12:07,059 --> 00:12:08,083
GUARD: There he is!

188
00:12:08,260 --> 00:12:10,228
lf... If I could just tell...

189
00:12:10,696 --> 00:12:13,597
GUARD: On the kettle!
That's him, right there!

190
00:12:18,003 --> 00:12:19,027
Look, up there!

191
00:12:26,779 --> 00:12:27,837
(SIGHS)

192
00:12:29,281 --> 00:12:31,112
Sweetie? Darling?

193
00:12:32,551 --> 00:12:34,075
She's... She's...

194
00:12:35,588 --> 00:12:38,216
She's...

195
00:12:38,924 --> 00:12:41,586
Blimey, she's dead. Get him!

196
00:12:41,694 --> 00:12:43,423
GUARD: Don't let him escape!

197
00:12:43,529 --> 00:12:45,759
We'll get you, you rowdy rat!

198
00:12:47,366 --> 00:12:48,526
Oh!

199
00:12:52,538 --> 00:12:53,562
No, no, no!

200
00:12:53,639 --> 00:12:55,368
No, not there!

201
00:13:45,958 --> 00:13:47,983
(SOBBING)

202
00:13:57,036 --> 00:13:59,163
You don't need to be afraid.

203
00:14:00,372 --> 00:14:03,341
I know it's dark,
but you'll get used to it.

204
00:14:04,043 --> 00:14:05,840
Who... Who are you?

205
00:14:06,645 --> 00:14:08,943
Just a rat, like you.

206
00:14:10,616 --> 00:14:12,049
Come with me.

207
00:14:24,496 --> 00:14:28,330
<i>NARRATOR: When something hurts
this much, there must be a reason.</i>

208
00:14:29,201 --> 00:14:31,499
<i>There must be someone to blame.</i>

209
00:14:35,341 --> 00:14:36,535
(CLEARS THROAT)

210
00:14:37,977 --> 00:14:41,140
"From this moment on, soup,

211
00:14:41,213 --> 00:14:46,742
"the making of soup,
the selling of soup, or the eating of soup,

212
00:14:47,019 --> 00:14:50,182
"is hereby outlawed
in the kingdom of Dor!

213
00:14:58,197 --> 00:15:01,564
"Rats are to be
considered illegal as well

214
00:15:01,667 --> 00:15:06,331
"and are hereby deemed
unlawful creatures in the kingdom of Dor!

215
00:15:06,405 --> 00:15:07,702
"From this moment on,

216
00:15:07,773 --> 00:15:13,040
"anyone harboring, sheltering
or possessing a rat in any way,

217
00:15:13,112 --> 00:15:15,672
"shall face the full wrath of the law!"

218
00:15:17,016 --> 00:15:18,847
<i>NARRATOR: So think about this.</i>

219
00:15:18,918 --> 00:15:23,719
<i>What happens when you make something</i>
<i>illegal that is just a natural part of the world?</i>

220
00:15:25,524 --> 00:15:27,583
<i>You may as well
make flies illegal.</i>

221
00:15:27,693 --> 00:15:29,888
<i>Or sweat. Or Monday morning.</i>

222
00:15:30,796 --> 00:15:34,254
<i>But that's what the King did</i>
<i>out of a terrible sadness.</i>

223
00:15:38,470 --> 00:15:41,064
<i>Sunlight left and
the world went gray.</i>

224
00:15:42,408 --> 00:15:46,435
<i>Colors faded into each other and</i>
<i>dark clouds filled the sky.</i>

225
00:15:48,547 --> 00:15:52,643
<i>And for a long time,
it wouldn't rain.</i>

226
00:15:56,322 --> 00:16:02,283
<i>The clouds just stayed</i>
<i>and stayed and stayed.</i>

227
00:16:08,767 --> 00:16:10,496
(SIGHS)

228
00:16:12,604 --> 00:16:14,435
I wish it would rain.

229
00:16:15,174 --> 00:16:16,664
You and the whole world, madam.

230
00:16:17,643 --> 00:16:18,667
Ow!

231
00:16:18,777 --> 00:16:19,903
Oh, sorry, milady!

232
00:16:20,579 --> 00:16:23,104
Well, at least I can still feel that.

233
00:16:26,151 --> 00:16:30,178
Louise, do you think
there's a bit of light

234
00:16:30,856 --> 00:16:31,982
somewhere in the world?

235
00:16:32,524 --> 00:16:33,616
Don't know, ma'am.

236
00:16:33,692 --> 00:16:35,319
I think there is.

237
00:16:36,261 --> 00:16:38,923
You just need to know where to find it.

238
00:16:51,076 --> 00:16:53,476
<i>NARRATOR: Okay, remember</i>
<i>when we told you how,</i>

239
00:16:53,579 --> 00:16:56,446
<i>once upon a time,</i>
<i>there was this brave little mouse?</i>

240
00:16:56,515 --> 00:17:00,076
<i>Well, if you know
anything about fairytales,</i>

241
00:17:00,152 --> 00:17:04,350
<i>you know that a
hero doesn't appear</i>

242
00:17:04,456 --> 00:17:06,754
<i>until the world really needs one.</i>

243
00:17:16,535 --> 00:17:18,162
(MICE SCREAMING)

244
00:17:20,706 --> 00:17:21,832
MOUSE: Oh, look out!

245
00:17:21,940 --> 00:17:25,137
Alms for the blind! Alms for the blind!

246
00:17:25,878 --> 00:17:26,936
(EXCLAIMS)

247
00:17:31,316 --> 00:17:32,374
(MICE CHATTERING)

248
00:18:03,348 --> 00:18:04,576
Excuse me. Excuse me.

249
00:18:05,184 --> 00:18:06,515
Excuse me.

250
00:18:06,985 --> 00:18:08,350
Excuse me.

251
00:18:09,088 --> 00:18:10,521
- Whoa!
- I'm sorry. Sorry.

252
00:18:10,589 --> 00:18:11,817
- Tilling?
- Oh!

253
00:18:12,191 --> 00:18:13,886
Mr. Mayor, hello!

254
00:18:13,992 --> 00:18:15,152
Where are you going?

255
00:18:15,227 --> 00:18:19,061
(STAMMERS) Oh, well,
my baby is having a...

256
00:18:19,164 --> 00:18:22,258
No, my wife is having a...

257
00:18:22,401 --> 00:18:24,494
Oh, right. Congratulations.

258
00:18:24,770 --> 00:18:26,101
Thank you. Thank you, sir.

259
00:18:26,705 --> 00:18:29,037
I'm sorry, I... I really... Goodbye.

260
00:18:38,050 --> 00:18:39,711
His eyes are open.

261
00:18:39,785 --> 00:18:41,184
Don't worry about it.

262
00:18:41,253 --> 00:18:42,948
Sometimes they are.

263
00:18:43,055 --> 00:18:44,579
But he isn't cowering.

264
00:18:44,690 --> 00:18:46,521
He's looking right at us.

265
00:18:46,592 --> 00:18:49,026
Don't worry. He'll learn to cower.

266
00:18:49,461 --> 00:18:51,224
They all do in time.

267
00:18:52,131 --> 00:18:53,621
ANTOINETTE: But he isn't!

268
00:19:00,472 --> 00:19:04,772
Wow! He's so puny!
And look at those ears!

269
00:19:05,777 --> 00:19:07,244
<i>NARRATOR: And,
from the very beginning,</i>

270
00:19:07,312 --> 00:19:09,542
<i>Despereaux Tilling heard more,</i>

271
00:19:09,615 --> 00:19:13,415
<i>saw more and even smelled more</i>
<i>than any of the other mice.</i>

272
00:19:19,224 --> 00:19:21,158
Despereaux, don't do it.

273
00:19:30,002 --> 00:19:31,060
(GASP)

274
00:19:32,404 --> 00:19:33,598
MOUSE 1: Don't look. Don't look!

275
00:19:33,672 --> 00:19:34,764
MOUSE 2: I won't, I won't.

276
00:19:35,908 --> 00:19:36,966
(GROANS)

277
00:19:42,948 --> 00:19:43,972
Mmm.

278
00:19:44,616 --> 00:19:47,483
<i>NARRATOR: Despereaux Tilling</i>
<i>had no idea he was small.</i>

279
00:19:48,587 --> 00:19:51,112
<i>He wasn't just small
in human terms.</i>

280
00:19:51,290 --> 00:19:53,758
<i>He was small even for a mouse.</i>

281
00:19:54,493 --> 00:19:57,587
<i>But, to tell you the truth,</i>
<i>he didn't even notice.</i>

282
00:19:57,863 --> 00:20:02,163
<i>In fact, in his own mind,</i>
<i>Despereaux was a giant.</i>

283
00:20:12,010 --> 00:20:13,807
We're worried about him.

284
00:20:13,879 --> 00:20:15,972
He doesn't scurry. He doesn't cower.

285
00:20:16,048 --> 00:20:18,312
At first, we thought he would
grow out of it, but...

286
00:20:18,383 --> 00:20:20,317
Well, he scurries sometimes.

287
00:20:20,385 --> 00:20:21,716
But not when he's scared!

288
00:20:21,820 --> 00:20:22,844
He just does it for fun.

289
00:20:22,955 --> 00:20:24,479
And he never cowers.

290
00:20:24,556 --> 00:20:25,682
We've showed him how, but he...

291
00:20:25,791 --> 00:20:28,282
Well, some kids are slower than others.

292
00:20:28,360 --> 00:20:30,487
He'll cower in time. We'll work on it.

293
00:20:30,562 --> 00:20:33,122
- Yes, but...
- It'll be fine, I promise.

294
00:20:33,832 --> 00:20:35,732
All right, settle down.

295
00:20:36,335 --> 00:20:37,802
Ready, class?

296
00:20:41,873 --> 00:20:42,897
(ALL GASP)

297
00:20:43,709 --> 00:20:44,835
Good.

298
00:20:47,179 --> 00:20:48,669
ALL: Mmm! Ah!

299
00:20:49,748 --> 00:20:51,340
Good. Excellent.

300
00:20:54,019 --> 00:20:56,146
(ALL SCREAM)

301
00:21:01,860 --> 00:21:04,192
- Despereaux!
- Yes?

302
00:21:04,263 --> 00:21:05,355
You didn't cower.

303
00:21:05,998 --> 00:21:07,022
Looks like a sword.

304
00:21:07,099 --> 00:21:09,590
It's a carving knife.

305
00:21:10,702 --> 00:21:12,897
It's beautiful!

306
00:21:13,005 --> 00:21:14,495
It's dangerous.

307
00:21:14,840 --> 00:21:16,831
Do you have anymore?

308
00:21:20,712 --> 00:21:22,703
Despereaux, what are you doing?

309
00:21:22,781 --> 00:21:24,271
We're not even supposed to be here.

310
00:21:24,383 --> 00:21:25,941
That's the dungeon.

311
00:21:26,051 --> 00:21:27,450
They have rats down there.

312
00:21:27,552 --> 00:21:29,042
And they'll eat you.

313
00:21:29,121 --> 00:21:31,021
And pull your arms off!

314
00:21:34,359 --> 00:21:36,054
How far down is it?

315
00:21:37,195 --> 00:21:39,561
I don't know. No one's ever come back.

316
00:21:39,631 --> 00:21:40,893
How come?

317
00:21:40,966 --> 00:21:42,433
'Cause... 'Cause...

318
00:21:42,601 --> 00:21:44,262
'Cause that's where
you go when you get...

319
00:21:44,369 --> 00:21:45,802
(STAMMERING) When you get...

320
00:21:45,904 --> 00:21:47,098
Banished.

321
00:21:48,106 --> 00:21:49,437
What do you get banished for?

322
00:21:49,741 --> 00:21:51,038
Oh, you know.

323
00:21:51,109 --> 00:21:52,371
- Rules and...
- Breaking.

324
00:21:52,477 --> 00:21:53,739
- We can't even...
- Talk about it...

325
00:21:53,812 --> 00:21:54,904
- Because...
- That's one of the...

326
00:21:55,580 --> 00:21:56,638
ALL: Rules!

327
00:21:59,418 --> 00:22:00,783
MOUSE 1: Despereaux!

328
00:22:02,421 --> 00:22:04,821
I just want to have a quick look.

329
00:22:05,057 --> 00:22:06,888
We got to get out of here!

330
00:22:08,960 --> 00:22:10,154
MOUSE 1: Oh, gosh.
MOUSE 2: Oh, no.

331
00:22:10,262 --> 00:22:11,388
ALL: Oh, jeez.

332
00:22:11,463 --> 00:22:12,623
Uh-oh.

333
00:22:27,412 --> 00:22:29,676
Despereaux! You can't feed them.

334
00:22:33,318 --> 00:22:34,785
Hello?

335
00:22:35,354 --> 00:22:38,915
(ECHOES)

336
00:22:40,826 --> 00:22:43,590
Here you go, whoever you are.

337
00:22:53,138 --> 00:22:54,264
(CHUCKLING) Nice.

338
00:23:28,240 --> 00:23:29,502
You are crazy!

339
00:23:29,574 --> 00:23:31,041
What I say? I said nothing!

340
00:23:31,143 --> 00:23:32,542
Well, you heard exactly what I said.

341
00:23:32,644 --> 00:23:34,202
- I say you crazy.
- No, no, no, no!

342
00:23:38,884 --> 00:23:40,647
(PLAYING MUSIC)

343
00:23:46,158 --> 00:23:47,887
(ALARM BELL RINGING)

344
00:23:50,529 --> 00:23:51,826
RAT: Hurry!

345
00:23:54,166 --> 00:23:55,758
(RATS CHANTING)

346
00:24:03,108 --> 00:24:05,338
(CROWD CHEERS)

347
00:24:05,410 --> 00:24:07,344
SMUDGE: Ha! They look hungry, sir.

348
00:24:07,412 --> 00:24:08,674
Mmm-hmm.

349
00:24:11,416 --> 00:24:12,781
Dinnertime.

350
00:24:14,719 --> 00:24:16,710
(CLAMORING)

351
00:24:19,724 --> 00:24:20,782
(CHUCKLES)

352
00:24:29,901 --> 00:24:31,528
You're not eating.

353
00:24:31,603 --> 00:24:33,969
Uh, I was.

354
00:24:34,072 --> 00:24:36,404
No, you weren't.

355
00:24:36,475 --> 00:24:39,911
Well, I'm just watching, sir.

356
00:24:40,378 --> 00:24:43,973
Well, that's not very grateful of you

357
00:24:44,082 --> 00:24:47,210
after I've taken you under my wing.

358
00:24:47,552 --> 00:24:51,921
(STAMMERING) Well, I'm grateful, really.
I am.

359
00:24:52,157 --> 00:24:54,091
You miss something, don't you?

360
00:24:54,159 --> 00:24:56,059
Uh, no, I don't.

361
00:24:56,228 --> 00:24:58,628
There's nothing up there, Roscuro.

362
00:24:59,231 --> 00:25:00,562
Nothing at all.

363
00:25:00,632 --> 00:25:03,100
Oh, no, I know that! Absolutely.

364
00:25:03,435 --> 00:25:06,029
Uh, nothing!

365
00:25:06,671 --> 00:25:08,662
Nothing. Nothing at all.

366
00:25:08,874 --> 00:25:10,364
He's a tough one.

367
00:25:10,475 --> 00:25:13,171
You're not gonna turn him.
Nah, you're not.

368
00:25:13,278 --> 00:25:17,806
Oh, I don't know. A rat is a rat.

369
00:25:18,316 --> 00:25:21,547
It doesn't really matter
where you come from.

370
00:25:51,383 --> 00:25:52,714
ROSCURO: I'm sorry.

371
00:26:04,763 --> 00:26:06,253
MOUSE: He is so weird.

372
00:26:06,431 --> 00:26:07,523
(LAUGHS) No kidding.

373
00:26:08,266 --> 00:26:10,234
That is so beautiful.

374
00:26:10,335 --> 00:26:11,666
I wonder what's out there.

375
00:26:30,522 --> 00:26:32,752
"February 1: Doesn't scurry.

376
00:26:32,857 --> 00:26:34,848
"February 3: Didn't cower.

377
00:26:34,926 --> 00:26:36,723
"Didn't cower. Didn't cower.

378
00:26:36,795 --> 00:26:38,262
"Wouldn't scurry."

379
00:26:38,363 --> 00:26:41,855
Oh, here's one:
"Drew pictures of cats on his notebook."

380
00:26:41,933 --> 00:26:43,958
- No! Cats?
- Oh! I can't imagine!

381
00:26:44,302 --> 00:26:47,465
I'm afraid so. Named it Fluffy.

382
00:26:48,106 --> 00:26:51,769
- Oh, I had no idea!
- Oh! That's terrible.

383
00:26:53,979 --> 00:26:55,776
- Despereaux.
- Yes, sir?

384
00:26:56,081 --> 00:26:57,378
Come in, please.

385
00:27:01,386 --> 00:27:03,377
Despereaux, why do you think
you're in school?

386
00:27:04,789 --> 00:27:05,915
To learn?

387
00:27:05,991 --> 00:27:07,083
- To learn, yes.
- Yes.

388
00:27:07,158 --> 00:27:08,216
To learn what?

389
00:27:09,394 --> 00:27:14,229
(HESITATING) To learn
how to be a mouse, sir.

390
00:27:14,666 --> 00:27:16,156
That is correct.

391
00:27:16,267 --> 00:27:18,667
And you can't be a mouse if
you don't learn to be afraid.

392
00:27:19,504 --> 00:27:21,233
Oh, Despereaux, this...

393
00:27:21,306 --> 00:27:24,275
There's so many
wonderful things in life to be afraid of

394
00:27:24,342 --> 00:27:26,242
if you'd just learn how scary they are.

395
00:27:26,411 --> 00:27:28,572
Yes. Yes, sir.

396
00:27:32,484 --> 00:27:33,746
How about his brother?

397
00:27:33,818 --> 00:27:35,149
His brother? What about him?

398
00:27:35,253 --> 00:27:38,188
Yes, is he, you know, timid?

399
00:27:38,823 --> 00:27:40,916
Oh! Oh, yes!

400
00:27:41,092 --> 00:27:42,753
- Yes, very timid.
- Yes. So timid!

401
00:27:42,827 --> 00:27:44,556
As timid as the day is long.

402
00:27:44,663 --> 00:27:45,994
Good. Good.

403
00:27:46,197 --> 00:27:48,859
Sometimes they just need
to see the older ones do it.

404
00:27:48,967 --> 00:27:50,491
No one starts out afraid.

405
00:27:50,869 --> 00:27:52,700
- Understood.
- Of course.

406
00:27:53,471 --> 00:27:54,995
- You coddle that boy, that's the problem.
- No.

407
00:27:55,073 --> 00:27:56,131
- Yes, you do.
- No, no.

408
00:27:56,207 --> 00:27:58,232
- Yes, you do. You've been doing it for years.
- He was always...

409
00:27:58,343 --> 00:27:59,367
He's little. I've had to help him.

410
00:27:59,477 --> 00:28:02,139
He's not going to be afraid unless
you allow him to be afraid.

411
00:28:02,213 --> 00:28:03,544
Well, Furlough will teach him.

412
00:28:09,854 --> 00:28:10,878
Do what he does.

413
00:28:10,989 --> 00:28:12,183
And don't do anything he doesn't.

414
00:28:12,257 --> 00:28:13,656
And if he's afraid of something...

415
00:28:13,725 --> 00:28:15,420
Then you need to be afraid of it, too.

416
00:28:36,347 --> 00:28:37,405
Oh!

417
00:28:42,253 --> 00:28:43,345
Wow.

418
00:28:56,935 --> 00:28:59,096
Come on, Furlough, hurry up!

419
00:29:03,108 --> 00:29:04,200
Whoa...

420
00:29:15,553 --> 00:29:18,420
FURLOUGH: All right, now, you start
nibbling right along that edge there.

421
00:29:19,257 --> 00:29:22,624
The glue is all right,
but it's the pages that taste the best.

422
00:29:23,294 --> 00:29:27,253
Hmm. "Once upon a time."
That's great, isn't it?

423
00:29:27,665 --> 00:29:29,155
"Upon a time."

424
00:29:29,334 --> 00:29:31,268
And they don't even tell you
what time that is yet.

425
00:29:31,336 --> 00:29:33,167
It's like you have to find that out.

426
00:29:33,271 --> 00:29:36,263
You're not supposed to read it, Despereaux.
You're supposed to eat it.

427
00:29:37,642 --> 00:29:39,940
Good. I'll come back in an hour.

428
00:29:41,112 --> 00:29:45,481
And no reading! It's a rule.

429
00:29:59,164 --> 00:30:02,930
<i>NARRATOR: Once upon a time,</i>
<i>there lived a fair princess,</i>

430
00:30:03,935 --> 00:30:06,335
<i>fairer than any in any other land.</i>

431
00:30:07,639 --> 00:30:09,300
Hmm. Fair.

432
00:30:10,141 --> 00:30:15,101
<i>And, as the story goes,</i>
<i>she was locked up in a faraway castle,</i>

433
00:30:15,213 --> 00:30:18,671
<i>where she could see the world</i>
<i>but could never touch it.</i>

434
00:30:21,519 --> 00:30:23,487
<i>She longed for a prince.</i>

435
00:30:24,322 --> 00:30:27,416
<i>A brave knight who would</i>
<i>deliver her from all of this.</i>

436
00:30:27,525 --> 00:30:31,427
<i>Someone with courage</i>
<i>and honor and decency.</i>

437
00:30:37,435 --> 00:30:39,562
<i>But in a cruel and
frightened world,</i>

438
00:30:39,671 --> 00:30:41,730
<i>men like this were scarce indeed.</i>

439
00:30:42,607 --> 00:30:43,665
(DRAGON ROARING)

440
00:30:45,210 --> 00:30:46,234
(GRUNTS)

441
00:31:23,615 --> 00:31:25,845
<i>They lived in a special world</i>

442
00:31:26,351 --> 00:31:29,809
<i>built on courage and
chivalry and honor.</i>

443
00:31:30,088 --> 00:31:32,249
<i>They pledged their
lives to each other.</i>

444
00:31:32,690 --> 00:31:35,989
<i>To fight for truth,
to defend the weak,</i>

445
00:31:36,094 --> 00:31:39,825
<i>to seek justice, and to always...</i>

446
00:31:44,502 --> 00:31:45,867
LESTER: How was the library?

447
00:31:45,970 --> 00:31:47,028
Fine.

448
00:31:47,605 --> 00:31:49,334
Spoil your appetite?

449
00:31:49,674 --> 00:31:51,938
No. Helped it, actually.

450
00:31:52,543 --> 00:31:54,170
Made me hungrier.

451
00:31:55,713 --> 00:31:56,975
Good lad.

452
00:32:00,051 --> 00:32:01,450
Ha-hah!

453
00:32:03,888 --> 00:32:07,380
Did you see they're putting up
a new front on the crumb shop?

454
00:32:07,492 --> 00:32:10,120
ANTOINETTE: Oh! But I loved the old front.
LESTER: Quite modern. Yes.

455
00:32:16,968 --> 00:32:19,163
<i>NARRATOR: Did a book
ever speak to you?</i>

456
00:32:19,504 --> 00:32:21,972
<i>Almost like it was
written for you?</i>

457
00:32:22,674 --> 00:32:24,642
<i>Despereaux loved it all.</i>

458
00:32:25,009 --> 00:32:26,636
<i>Every bit of it.</i>

459
00:32:26,811 --> 00:32:30,178
<i>The truth, the justice,
the bravery,</i>

460
00:32:30,515 --> 00:32:32,244
<i>the sword-fighting.</i>

461
00:32:34,319 --> 00:32:37,152
<i>He even loved things
you wouldn't suspect.</i>

462
00:32:38,189 --> 00:32:40,521
<i>The story said she was a prisoner,</i>

463
00:32:40,591 --> 00:32:42,752
<i>but that wasn't totally true</i>

464
00:32:42,894 --> 00:32:46,830
<i>because she had hope,</i>
<i>and whenever you have hope,</i>

465
00:32:46,898 --> 00:32:49,059
<i>you're never really
anybody's prisoner.</i>

466
00:32:49,701 --> 00:32:51,828
Someday, my prince will come.

467
00:32:52,437 --> 00:32:54,496
<i>But how did she know that?</i>

468
00:32:54,739 --> 00:32:56,866
Yeah, how did she know that?

469
00:32:58,943 --> 00:33:00,934
(LUTE PLAYING)

470
00:33:11,122 --> 00:33:12,180
(SNIFFLES)

471
00:33:24,769 --> 00:33:25,793
(GASPS)

472
00:33:38,649 --> 00:33:39,911
(PRINCESS PEA CRYING)

473
00:33:45,123 --> 00:33:46,590
DESPEREAUX: Why are you crying?

474
00:33:46,657 --> 00:33:47,681
(GASPS)

475
00:33:48,993 --> 00:33:50,790
Why are you crying?

476
00:33:52,296 --> 00:33:53,923
Down here.

477
00:33:54,198 --> 00:33:55,529
(GASPS) Are you a rat?

478
00:33:55,933 --> 00:33:56,957
No.

479
00:33:57,035 --> 00:33:58,696
What are you? A mouse?

480
00:34:01,672 --> 00:34:03,139
I am a gentleman.

481
00:34:04,108 --> 00:34:05,132
(CHUCKLES)

482
00:34:06,110 --> 00:34:07,634
And how do you do?

483
00:34:10,114 --> 00:34:11,138
You're sad.

484
00:34:11,983 --> 00:34:13,041
Yes.

485
00:34:13,351 --> 00:34:14,443
Because you have longing.

486
00:34:16,687 --> 00:34:18,177
You're a strange little mouse.

487
00:34:18,990 --> 00:34:20,014
Thank you.

488
00:34:23,728 --> 00:34:24,990
Come on.

489
00:34:33,071 --> 00:34:34,470
Where did you hear that?

490
00:34:35,373 --> 00:34:36,965
About the longing.

491
00:34:37,041 --> 00:34:38,372
In a story.

492
00:34:38,476 --> 00:34:40,501
A story? About what?

493
00:34:40,978 --> 00:34:43,708
About a princess, like you,
in a castle, like this.

494
00:34:44,849 --> 00:34:47,750
Oh. You're a smooth little mouse,
aren't you?

495
00:34:49,020 --> 00:34:51,488
Bet you tell that to all the princesses.

496
00:34:51,889 --> 00:34:53,720
I am sworn to tell the truth.

497
00:34:53,991 --> 00:34:55,424
It is a code of honor.

498
00:34:55,526 --> 00:35:00,259
Ah. Not just a gentleman,
an honorable gentleman.

499
00:35:01,732 --> 00:35:04,428
Well, then, how does this story end

500
00:35:04,535 --> 00:35:06,696
with this princess
who's locked in a castle?

501
00:35:06,771 --> 00:35:08,204
I don't know...

502
00:35:08,506 --> 00:35:10,030
I haven't finished it yet.

503
00:35:11,109 --> 00:35:12,508
I'd love to know.

504
00:35:13,544 --> 00:35:15,512
Oh, I wish it would rain.

505
00:35:15,947 --> 00:35:18,074
I wish there was soup again.

506
00:35:18,249 --> 00:35:20,376
I even wish there were rats!

507
00:35:21,552 --> 00:35:23,281
Will you promise me that?

508
00:35:23,387 --> 00:35:25,912
Will you promise to finish your story
and tell me how it ends?

509
00:35:26,457 --> 00:35:28,925
Yes. It will be my quest.

510
00:35:29,927 --> 00:35:33,294
Your quest! You are a very brave mouse.

511
00:35:39,704 --> 00:35:41,865
Thank you, my good gentleman.

512
00:35:48,146 --> 00:35:49,204
Whoa!

513
00:35:51,816 --> 00:35:52,942
Whoa.

514
00:35:57,989 --> 00:35:59,047
(EXCLAIMS)

515
00:36:02,460 --> 00:36:03,484
Whoa!

516
00:36:06,164 --> 00:36:07,256
(EXCLAIMS)

517
00:36:17,341 --> 00:36:20,674
<i>NARRATOR: Now, there are</i>
<i>all kinds of princesses.</i>

518
00:36:22,446 --> 00:36:24,346
<i>Some are born that way,</i>

519
00:36:24,448 --> 00:36:26,143
<i>some marry into it,</i>

520
00:36:26,350 --> 00:36:29,979
<i>and some are destined
to be princesses</i>

521
00:36:30,054 --> 00:36:31,487
<i>only in their own minds.</i>

522
00:36:33,191 --> 00:36:34,852
<i>But at one time or another,</i>

523
00:36:34,959 --> 00:36:37,985
<i>every little girl
longs to be a princess.</i>

524
00:36:40,298 --> 00:36:41,959
I'm gonna live right there.

525
00:36:42,066 --> 00:36:45,001
Right up there, near the tippy-top.

526
00:36:46,304 --> 00:36:49,637
Quit your daydreaming
and feed those swine!

527
00:36:50,341 --> 00:36:52,901
Yes, I know. It's gonna be all mine.

528
00:36:53,678 --> 00:36:58,581
No, you deaf little urchin.
I said feed those swine!

529
00:36:58,683 --> 00:36:59,707
(EARS RINGING)

530
00:37:02,320 --> 00:37:04,379
<i>NARRATOR: Miggery Sow had been</i>
<i>shoveling slop</i>

531
00:37:04,488 --> 00:37:06,547
<i>for as long as she could remember.</i>

532
00:37:06,757 --> 00:37:10,557
<i>Her Uncle Ned had put a shovel in her
hand from the minute she could hold one.</i>

533
00:37:11,362 --> 00:37:13,387
<i>But it turned out all right</i>

534
00:37:13,497 --> 00:37:15,488
<i>because she got on</i>
<i>quite nicely with the pigs.</i>

535
00:37:15,566 --> 00:37:17,033
That's right.

536
00:37:17,335 --> 00:37:21,237
I'm gonna have a special room
just for my dresses

537
00:37:21,505 --> 00:37:25,100
and another whole closet
just for my knickers!

538
00:37:25,243 --> 00:37:29,111
<i>In fact, Miggery Sow could</i>
<i>see her future so clearly.</i>

539
00:37:29,714 --> 00:37:33,878
<i>She could see the tiara, the fancy dresses,</i>
<i>the maids-in-waiting,</i>

540
00:37:34,552 --> 00:37:37,544
<i>and when things got</i>
<i>really bad around the farm,</i>

541
00:37:37,622 --> 00:37:42,025
<i>she could see the moment that she would
finally be delivered from all of this.</i>

542
00:37:42,460 --> 00:37:43,859
Not long now.

543
00:37:43,928 --> 00:37:45,623
I promise you that.

544
00:37:46,063 --> 00:37:50,727
20 for the big ones,
15 for the sow, and 12 for the girl.

545
00:37:51,202 --> 00:37:53,762
15 for the girl, same as the sow.

546
00:37:55,239 --> 00:37:58,868
I told you! I told you
I'd make it to the castle!

547
00:37:58,976 --> 00:38:00,466
Whoa!

548
00:38:02,113 --> 00:38:05,310
<i>So sometimes, it doesn't take much</i>
<i>for your dreams to come true.</i>

549
00:38:06,284 --> 00:38:09,151
<i>You just have to be
able to see it that way.</i>

550
00:38:09,954 --> 00:38:13,446
She was beautiful! Like an angel.

551
00:38:13,958 --> 00:38:15,619
FURLOUGH: You are crazy.

552
00:38:15,793 --> 00:38:18,455
And she smelled so amazing.

553
00:38:19,063 --> 00:38:20,223
Like a garden.

554
00:38:20,731 --> 00:38:21,755
Despereaux!

555
00:38:21,832 --> 00:38:23,823
You can't talk to a human.

556
00:38:23,934 --> 00:38:25,401
That is the worst thing you can do.

557
00:38:25,469 --> 00:38:27,403
No, it's the best thing I ever did.

558
00:38:27,571 --> 00:38:28,936
They will throw you in the dungeon.

559
00:38:29,006 --> 00:38:30,564
You will get eaten by rats!

560
00:38:30,641 --> 00:38:31,903
It would be worth it.

561
00:38:32,343 --> 00:38:34,311
They could tear at my flesh.

562
00:38:34,412 --> 00:38:35,777
Oh, this is bad.

563
00:38:35,846 --> 00:38:38,280
Oh, and when she held me
in her hand, it was...

564
00:38:38,849 --> 00:38:42,182
It was so soft,
like floating in a pillow.

565
00:38:42,553 --> 00:38:43,986
You know what? I'm worried about you.

566
00:38:44,322 --> 00:38:45,983
That's the point, Furlough.

567
00:38:46,057 --> 00:38:47,854
There's nothing to be afraid of.

568
00:38:47,958 --> 00:38:49,949
Quiet! They will hear you.

569
00:38:50,027 --> 00:38:51,790
Come on. Just try it.

570
00:38:52,063 --> 00:38:54,793
Just for a second, just try being brave.

571
00:38:54,965 --> 00:38:56,796
- Oh!
- And stop cowering!

572
00:38:56,901 --> 00:38:59,165
What's going on in here?

573
00:38:59,236 --> 00:39:03,900
What's all this talk
about princesses and bravery?

574
00:39:04,909 --> 00:39:07,537
Furlough, I want to see you
in my study, right now.

575
00:39:11,082 --> 00:39:13,312
LESTER: Are you sure?
FURLOUGH: That's what he said.

576
00:39:13,384 --> 00:39:15,818
- A real human?
- A princess.

577
00:39:15,886 --> 00:39:16,910
(SIGHS)

578
00:39:17,488 --> 00:39:18,580
We need to tell them.

579
00:39:18,689 --> 00:39:20,247
We need to tell the Mouse Council.

580
00:39:20,358 --> 00:39:22,656
- But they'll...
- This is bad. This is very bad.

581
00:39:22,727 --> 00:39:25,719
If they find out...
If they find out that they didn't find out...

582
00:39:25,830 --> 00:39:28,856
Oh, then they'll find
out that it was me who...

583
00:39:28,933 --> 00:39:30,025
Oh, no.

584
00:39:30,101 --> 00:39:32,262
But they will send him to the dungeon!

585
00:39:32,670 --> 00:39:35,230
- Oh, he'll get eaten by rats!
- Oh!

586
00:39:35,339 --> 00:39:36,829
No, not if we beg.

587
00:39:36,907 --> 00:39:40,934
If we really beg
and show them that he's changed.

588
00:39:41,345 --> 00:39:42,676
That he's afraid.

589
00:39:42,747 --> 00:39:46,239
That he's afraid,
and he's turned into a real mouse.

590
00:39:47,017 --> 00:39:48,382
Despereaux!

591
00:39:57,962 --> 00:40:00,522
<i>NARRATOR: Of course,</i>
<i>destiny is a funny thing.</i>

592
00:40:01,132 --> 00:40:04,761
<i>We go out to meet it,</i>
<i>and we don't always know that we are.</i>

593
00:40:14,311 --> 00:40:15,869
KNIGHT: For glory and honor!

594
00:40:15,980 --> 00:40:17,447
Surround him!

595
00:40:34,965 --> 00:40:36,262
MAYOR: Despereaux Tilling.

596
00:40:36,333 --> 00:40:37,391
(GASPS)

597
00:40:39,403 --> 00:40:42,270
How long have you been
working on this book?

598
00:40:42,339 --> 00:40:44,330
Hmm... A week?

599
00:40:44,442 --> 00:40:46,672
A week? You've hardly cracked it.

600
00:40:47,511 --> 00:40:49,001
Well, I was...

601
00:40:50,347 --> 00:40:52,144
I just wanted to see how it ends.

602
00:40:53,083 --> 00:40:55,313
(BELL TOLLS)

603
00:40:57,655 --> 00:40:58,917
(CROWD MURMURING)

604
00:41:02,860 --> 00:41:04,953
INQUISITOR: Refused training as a mouse.

605
00:41:05,029 --> 00:41:08,487
Refused to respect the will
and guidance of elder mice.

606
00:41:08,933 --> 00:41:12,596
Repeatedly engaged in bold
and un-meek behavior.

607
00:41:12,703 --> 00:41:17,697
Triggered willfully
not less than 17 mousetraps.

608
00:41:17,842 --> 00:41:18,866
(CROWD GASPS)

609
00:41:18,976 --> 00:41:20,034
Just shameful!

610
00:41:20,144 --> 00:41:22,339
Had personal contact with...

611
00:41:23,047 --> 00:41:24,071
With...

612
00:41:27,084 --> 00:41:28,210
With a human being.

613
00:41:28,319 --> 00:41:30,082
(CROWD MURMURING)

614
00:41:30,221 --> 00:41:32,348
Isn't there something you can do?

615
00:41:32,423 --> 00:41:34,482
Antoinette, stop right now! Stop that.

616
00:41:34,558 --> 00:41:36,025
You have to trust them.

617
00:41:36,093 --> 00:41:37,651
They are the Council.

618
00:41:37,728 --> 00:41:39,923
They're the Council because...

619
00:41:40,197 --> 00:41:42,722
Because they're the Council.

620
00:41:44,368 --> 00:41:45,835
They're the Council.

621
00:41:46,504 --> 00:41:48,233
Is there anything you wish to say
in your defense?

622
00:41:49,240 --> 00:41:53,006
Well, it was a very good story,

623
00:41:53,878 --> 00:41:57,370
and she was a very beautiful princess.

624
00:41:57,948 --> 00:41:59,415
(CROWD MURMURING)

625
00:42:00,117 --> 00:42:02,051
Despereaux Tilling,

626
00:42:02,119 --> 00:42:05,714
our laws are here
to protect us and our way of life.

627
00:42:06,357 --> 00:42:09,884
And when one of our citizens
strays from that way of life,

628
00:42:10,261 --> 00:42:12,525
he becomes a threat to us all.

629
00:42:13,130 --> 00:42:15,030
It's an easy question.

630
00:42:15,933 --> 00:42:18,299
Are you a man or are you a mouse?

631
00:42:21,372 --> 00:42:22,703
And your actions have told us

632
00:42:22,773 --> 00:42:25,799
that you have a great deal
of trouble being a mouse.

633
00:42:27,244 --> 00:42:29,109
It is the judgment of this court

634
00:42:29,213 --> 00:42:31,773
that you should be banished
from these walls forever.

635
00:42:32,449 --> 00:42:36,249
You shall be remanded into the
custody of Hovis, the Threadmaster,

636
00:42:36,320 --> 00:42:39,585
who will prepare you for your
descent into the dungeons of Dor,

637
00:42:39,657 --> 00:42:43,252
from which no mouse
and no light has ever escaped.

638
00:42:55,339 --> 00:42:57,500
- Shh!
- My baby!

639
00:42:57,641 --> 00:43:01,236
Quiet. Be quiet, my dear.
There's nothing to be done.

640
00:43:26,770 --> 00:43:28,203
Come with me.

641
00:43:36,647 --> 00:43:38,012
Stand there.

642
00:43:49,360 --> 00:43:50,418
Red?

643
00:43:50,728 --> 00:43:52,662
Ah, so they tell me.

644
00:43:55,032 --> 00:43:57,000
So you're the brave one.

645
00:43:58,102 --> 00:43:59,228
I guess.

646
00:43:59,336 --> 00:44:01,861
It's good. It'll carry well down there.

647
00:44:03,574 --> 00:44:05,201
Wear it proudly.

648
00:44:06,043 --> 00:44:07,567
There's no shame.

649
00:44:10,414 --> 00:44:11,711
It's time.

650
00:44:14,551 --> 00:44:17,884
It's all right.
They're too scared to come down here.

651
00:44:24,294 --> 00:44:25,556
In there?

652
00:44:25,929 --> 00:44:27,419
I'm afraid so.

653
00:44:29,266 --> 00:44:30,790
Courage, right?

654
00:44:30,901 --> 00:44:32,232
And truth.

655
00:44:32,803 --> 00:44:34,771
- And honor.
- Good.

656
00:44:34,872 --> 00:44:37,432
But especially courage.

657
00:44:49,253 --> 00:44:50,277
I'm ready.

658
00:44:50,387 --> 00:44:52,412
All right, then you need to...

659
00:44:55,459 --> 00:44:56,551
(EXCLAIMS)

660
00:45:09,139 --> 00:45:10,163
(GROANS)

661
00:45:30,294 --> 00:45:31,818
What? Whoa!

662
00:46:12,035 --> 00:46:14,333
(SNORING)

663
00:46:18,242 --> 00:46:20,073
(RATS CHATTERING)

664
00:46:28,018 --> 00:46:30,987
Hello? Hello?

665
00:46:32,189 --> 00:46:33,213
(GRUMBLES)

666
00:46:33,690 --> 00:46:34,714
Whoa!

667
00:46:37,394 --> 00:46:38,486
(WHISTLES)

668
00:46:38,562 --> 00:46:39,893
Lads, let's go, on the double!

669
00:46:39,997 --> 00:46:41,021
(EXCLAIMS)

670
00:46:43,734 --> 00:46:44,758
Who is that?

671
00:46:45,335 --> 00:46:46,666
Who goes there?

672
00:46:47,571 --> 00:46:48,833
Who is that?

673
00:46:48,906 --> 00:46:50,430
Despereaux Tilling.

674
00:46:50,541 --> 00:46:52,736
Are you a man or are you a mouse?

675
00:46:54,611 --> 00:46:57,239
I am a gentleman.

676
00:46:57,614 --> 00:46:59,081
(CHUCKLING) Oh.

677
00:46:59,516 --> 00:47:00,574
(RATS CLAMORING)

678
00:47:00,684 --> 00:47:02,242
- It's a mouse.
- I'm hungry.

679
00:47:02,352 --> 00:47:05,378
Shh! Quiet, lads. Patience.

680
00:47:06,723 --> 00:47:09,248
And what makes you a gentleman?

681
00:47:09,760 --> 00:47:11,022
A code...

682
00:47:11,094 --> 00:47:12,391
A code of honor.

683
00:47:12,462 --> 00:47:13,520
(LAUGHS)

684
00:47:13,597 --> 00:47:15,724
You're a strange little
mouse, aren't you?

685
00:47:15,799 --> 00:47:18,267
And where did you find
this code of honor?

686
00:47:18,368 --> 00:47:20,302
Well, in a legend.

687
00:47:20,404 --> 00:47:21,803
A legend that I read.

688
00:47:21,905 --> 00:47:24,635
Fine. Oh, tell me this legend of yours.

689
00:47:24,741 --> 00:47:26,971
I could do with a good story right now.

690
00:47:27,277 --> 00:47:28,608
Well,

691
00:47:28,712 --> 00:47:31,112
it's about a princess and a knight

692
00:47:32,282 --> 00:47:34,273
and his quest to save her honor.

693
00:47:34,751 --> 00:47:38,084
Ah. It was a princess
that took away my soup.

694
00:47:38,589 --> 00:47:40,079
She didn't take it.

695
00:47:40,157 --> 00:47:42,284
In fact, she misses it, too!

696
00:47:42,392 --> 00:47:43,484
(RATS MURMURING)

697
00:47:43,594 --> 00:47:45,721
How do you know all this, then?

698
00:47:45,796 --> 00:47:46,888
I've seen her.

699
00:47:47,231 --> 00:47:48,960
- Seen her?
- I've talked to her.

700
00:47:49,066 --> 00:47:51,500
- Talked to her?
- That's why they sent me down here.

701
00:47:51,602 --> 00:47:53,900
Mmm-hmm.
And what did this princess tell you

702
00:47:53,971 --> 00:47:55,632
when you had your little audience?

703
00:47:55,739 --> 00:47:57,138
(LAUGHING) Eh? Eh?

704
00:47:57,241 --> 00:48:00,005
Oh, you must be a royal mouse.
Is that it?

705
00:48:00,477 --> 00:48:04,004
She told me that
she missed the soup and the rain

706
00:48:04,748 --> 00:48:06,648
and, most of all, the sunlight.

707
00:48:07,351 --> 00:48:09,945
And that she just
wanted it all to come back again.

708
00:48:13,357 --> 00:48:14,949
Well, I don't want to
hear your little stories

709
00:48:15,025 --> 00:48:16,959
about princesses and sunshine.

710
00:48:17,928 --> 00:48:19,759
Go tell them to the rats!

711
00:48:19,963 --> 00:48:20,987
(GRUNTS)

712
00:48:21,465 --> 00:48:22,955
(RATS MURMURING)

713
00:48:26,436 --> 00:48:27,698
All right, boys, come on!

714
00:48:27,804 --> 00:48:29,362
(RATS SHOUTING)

715
00:48:41,852 --> 00:48:43,183
(CROWD CHEERING)

716
00:48:54,898 --> 00:48:55,956
(GRUNTING)

717
00:49:05,876 --> 00:49:06,900
(LAUGHING)

718
00:49:08,245 --> 00:49:09,542
Good crowd, isn't it, sir?

719
00:49:10,147 --> 00:49:12,172
Yes, it is, quite.

720
00:49:12,249 --> 00:49:14,376
CROWD: (CHANTING) Mouse! Mouse!
Mouse! Mouse!

721
00:49:21,358 --> 00:49:24,691
Ah, Roscuro! I'm glad you could make it.

722
00:49:24,761 --> 00:49:27,252
I thought you didn't like the arena.

723
00:49:27,364 --> 00:49:30,492
Huh? Oh! No, no.
It... It's an honor, sir.

724
00:49:31,168 --> 00:49:32,226
Oh!

725
00:49:32,336 --> 00:49:33,530
- BOTTICELLl: Good.
- Mmm.

726
00:49:33,704 --> 00:49:35,729
Well, enjoy.

727
00:49:36,173 --> 00:49:39,199
(STAMMERING) Oh, uh... Thank you.

728
00:49:39,276 --> 00:49:41,073
(CROWD CHEERING)

729
00:49:44,214 --> 00:49:46,182
Let the games begin!

730
00:49:54,725 --> 00:49:55,749
(ANIMAL SQUEALING)

731
00:49:59,529 --> 00:50:02,191
CROWD: (CHANTING) Mouse! Mouse! Mouse!

732
00:50:07,938 --> 00:50:09,303
(MEOWING)

733
00:50:09,473 --> 00:50:10,906
(CROWD CHEERING)

734
00:50:19,583 --> 00:50:20,880
(CROWD GROANING)

735
00:50:20,951 --> 00:50:21,975
RAT: Come on!

736
00:50:25,989 --> 00:50:27,286
(SNARLS)

737
00:50:27,424 --> 00:50:28,448
(MEOWS)

738
00:50:31,294 --> 00:50:32,886
(CROWD CHEERING)

739
00:50:35,732 --> 00:50:36,756
(SQUEALS)

740
00:51:03,693 --> 00:51:04,751
(SNARLS)

741
00:51:05,495 --> 00:51:06,519
Hold on!

742
00:51:12,869 --> 00:51:15,201
CROWD: (CHANTING) Eat! Eat! Eat!

743
00:51:20,477 --> 00:51:22,138
(RAT SHOUTING)

744
00:51:25,148 --> 00:51:26,172
ROSCURO: Wait!

745
00:51:26,516 --> 00:51:30,316
(STAMMERING) Can I have him?
Can I have this one? Please?

746
00:51:30,687 --> 00:51:32,655
(CROWD GRUMBLING)

747
00:51:33,957 --> 00:51:34,981
What?

748
00:51:35,392 --> 00:51:38,691
It's just that that one looks tasty.

749
00:51:38,862 --> 00:51:41,490
Well, this is progress.

750
00:51:41,565 --> 00:51:45,729
Perhaps we're starting
to leave the past behind us, eh?

751
00:51:45,836 --> 00:51:48,236
Enjoy, my friend.

752
00:51:48,338 --> 00:51:50,568
Don't leave a morsel.

753
00:51:50,674 --> 00:51:52,972
(STAMMERING) Oh, I won't.

754
00:51:53,844 --> 00:51:54,902
(SNAPS)

755
00:51:55,011 --> 00:51:56,035
Pull!

756
00:51:57,714 --> 00:51:58,738
(WHIMPERS)

757
00:51:58,915 --> 00:52:00,712
(CROWD GRUMBLING)

758
00:52:03,520 --> 00:52:05,351
(ALL CLAMORING)

759
00:52:12,362 --> 00:52:14,830
Come on, let's go, buster!

760
00:52:15,198 --> 00:52:18,190
That's it. That's it. You keep moving!

761
00:52:20,270 --> 00:52:23,103
(WHISPERING) It's okay. Keep walking.

762
00:52:23,373 --> 00:52:26,900
Come on, keep moving! Let's go, come on!

763
00:52:28,912 --> 00:52:30,345
(WHISPERING) It's right up there.

764
00:52:38,388 --> 00:52:40,049
- Huh?
- Keep walking.

765
00:52:47,697 --> 00:52:49,062
- Oh.
- See that?

766
00:52:50,133 --> 00:52:51,964
Light. Real light.

767
00:52:53,470 --> 00:52:55,938
It's mine, but you can share it.

768
00:52:56,606 --> 00:53:00,599
It isn't much, but there isn't much
anywhere since everything turned gray.

769
00:53:02,646 --> 00:53:04,273
You're not gonna eat me?

770
00:53:04,748 --> 00:53:06,943
No. I don't eat mice.

771
00:53:07,284 --> 00:53:08,717
Then what do you eat?

772
00:53:08,952 --> 00:53:10,078
Crumbs.

773
00:53:10,153 --> 00:53:11,484
When I can find them.

774
00:53:12,989 --> 00:53:15,321
So you are a gentleman.

775
00:53:18,094 --> 00:53:19,652
Tell me that story.

776
00:53:20,597 --> 00:53:22,064
About the Princess.

777
00:53:22,899 --> 00:53:24,764
Tell me what she looked like.

778
00:53:25,335 --> 00:53:27,132
Well, she was...

779
00:53:27,237 --> 00:53:28,499
Was she angry?

780
00:53:28,605 --> 00:53:29,799
No.

781
00:53:29,906 --> 00:53:31,567
No, not at all.

782
00:53:31,641 --> 00:53:34,576
Her heart was full of longing.

783
00:53:36,179 --> 00:53:37,771
What's longing?

784
00:53:39,683 --> 00:53:42,584
<i>NARRATOR: And that's</i>
<i>how a friendship is born.</i>

785
00:53:43,320 --> 00:53:47,313
<i>Over the next few weeks, he told Roscuro</i>
<i>everything he knew about loyalty</i>

786
00:53:47,424 --> 00:53:49,756
<i>and honor and
chivalry and courage.</i>

787
00:53:49,826 --> 00:53:53,159
<i>He told him about the Princess,</i>
<i>and where her longing came from.</i>

788
00:53:53,263 --> 00:53:57,097
<i>That she missed the rain and
the soup and even the rats.</i>

789
00:53:58,401 --> 00:53:59,493
Even the rats?

790
00:54:00,237 --> 00:54:04,401
<i>NARRATOR: He told him about their</i>
<i>code of honor, about his noble quest,</i>

791
00:54:04,841 --> 00:54:07,139
<i>about duty and loyalty.</i>

792
00:54:07,677 --> 00:54:10,771
<i>And there, in the
darkness of the cellar,</i>

793
00:54:10,847 --> 00:54:15,978
<i>two knights pledged devotion to a
princess who was trapped inside a castle.</i>

794
00:54:17,287 --> 00:54:19,812
<i>Trapped in a life full
of pain and longing.</i>

795
00:54:19,923 --> 00:54:21,823
<i>Even if no one could tell.</i>

796
00:54:25,962 --> 00:54:27,793
Your crown, ma'am.

797
00:54:29,032 --> 00:54:30,124
Oh.

798
00:54:31,167 --> 00:54:32,759
I don't want it today.

799
00:54:32,836 --> 00:54:34,633
But it's beautiful, ma'am.

800
00:54:34,971 --> 00:54:37,132
I know, but I don't want it.

801
00:54:37,207 --> 00:54:39,801
You look so pretty in it, ma'am.

802
00:54:39,876 --> 00:54:41,776
Like a princess.

803
00:54:42,045 --> 00:54:45,037
I know. I am the princess.

804
00:54:45,282 --> 00:54:46,840
Oh, I know, ma'am,

805
00:54:46,950 --> 00:54:51,148
but such a fine princess,
with a little, pretty, glittery...

806
00:54:51,221 --> 00:54:52,848
I don't want it!

807
00:54:52,956 --> 00:54:54,355
All right, Mig?

808
00:54:55,358 --> 00:54:56,985
Very well, ma'am.

809
00:54:57,627 --> 00:54:59,322
Please, take it away.

810
00:55:16,379 --> 00:55:17,403
MIG: Princess.

811
00:55:18,548 --> 00:55:20,038
Who's the princess?

812
00:55:20,684 --> 00:55:22,311
I'm a princess.

813
00:55:22,385 --> 00:55:24,319
I'm the princess.

814
00:55:26,156 --> 00:55:30,991
My comb, my hat, my gloves

815
00:55:32,028 --> 00:55:36,021
and my pretty powder

816
00:55:36,099 --> 00:55:38,659
on my pretty princess face.

817
00:55:38,835 --> 00:55:40,996
And what do you think you're doing?

818
00:55:41,071 --> 00:55:42,095
Ma'am!

819
00:55:42,205 --> 00:55:44,765
Where did you get all this?

820
00:55:44,874 --> 00:55:46,705
I just borrowed it, ma'am.

821
00:55:46,776 --> 00:55:47,902
Borrowed it?

822
00:55:48,244 --> 00:55:50,269
I was gonna put them all back.

823
00:55:50,413 --> 00:55:51,744
See that you do!

824
00:55:53,216 --> 00:55:56,083
And you can spend the whole week

825
00:55:56,186 --> 00:55:58,017
taking slop to the dungeon

826
00:55:58,088 --> 00:56:00,181
for your little escapade.

827
00:56:01,091 --> 00:56:02,422
"Princess"!

828
00:56:06,062 --> 00:56:08,963
God! She's the princess.

829
00:56:09,065 --> 00:56:10,123
(SCOFFS)

830
00:56:10,233 --> 00:56:14,863
And now I have to carry the sloppy,
gloppy, stinky stew

831
00:56:14,938 --> 00:56:17,634
down in the damp, dark, dingy...

832
00:56:19,876 --> 00:56:22,208
A person could get
lost forever down here.

833
00:56:24,314 --> 00:56:25,406
Oh!

834
00:56:25,482 --> 00:56:26,540
(SNORING)

835
00:56:27,083 --> 00:56:28,107
Din-din.

836
00:56:29,619 --> 00:56:30,643
Slop.

837
00:56:33,056 --> 00:56:36,719
No, don't stop! I said "slop"!

838
00:56:40,497 --> 00:56:41,589
(SIGHS)

839
00:56:41,664 --> 00:56:44,064
How am I supposed to eat this swill?

840
00:56:45,101 --> 00:56:48,434
Oh, stop that!
I don't have to be putting up with all this!

841
00:56:49,939 --> 00:56:51,634
I serve the Princess.

842
00:56:52,308 --> 00:56:53,673
(LAUGHING)

843
00:56:53,810 --> 00:56:56,472
Right. You serve the Princess.

844
00:56:56,579 --> 00:56:59,480
- That's a bit of a laugh, isn't it?
- I do.

845
00:56:59,582 --> 00:57:02,312
- I bring her tea and...
- Well, I don't want to hear it!

846
00:57:03,186 --> 00:57:05,154
Had me own little princess once.

847
00:57:05,688 --> 00:57:06,916
And now I don't.

848
00:57:07,357 --> 00:57:09,951
Oh. What, you had a princess?

849
00:57:11,861 --> 00:57:12,919
Yeah.

850
00:57:12,996 --> 00:57:15,294
Every dad's got a princess.

851
00:57:16,032 --> 00:57:18,091
<i>GREGORY: Till he stops being a dad,</i>
<i>of course.</i>

852
00:57:18,201 --> 00:57:19,463
(BABY COOING)

853
00:57:21,104 --> 00:57:23,937
Sorry. So, so, sorry!

854
00:57:25,642 --> 00:57:27,542
Oh, well, I've got a real one.

855
00:57:27,644 --> 00:57:30,704
And she's got a tiara and fancy robes,

856
00:57:30,814 --> 00:57:33,544
and she's got shiny bits
all over every frock in her closet.

857
00:57:33,650 --> 00:57:36,517
And I get to see her every single day.

858
00:57:37,620 --> 00:57:39,178
DESPEREAUX: What kind of a quest?

859
00:57:39,289 --> 00:57:40,313
Uh...

860
00:57:41,124 --> 00:57:42,887
To right a terrible wrong.

861
00:57:43,359 --> 00:57:45,327
But who did you wrong?

862
00:57:48,198 --> 00:57:49,222
Okay.

863
00:57:50,800 --> 00:57:53,496
Do you remember when
they banished the rats?

864
00:57:54,037 --> 00:57:55,698
- Sure. Yes.
- Okay.

865
00:57:56,539 --> 00:57:58,507
Well, it wasn't all
the rats they banished.

866
00:57:58,575 --> 00:58:03,012
I mean, they did, but it was
all because of one particular rat

867
00:58:03,847 --> 00:58:05,371
in particular.

868
00:58:05,515 --> 00:58:06,539
Oh.

869
00:58:07,817 --> 00:58:08,841
Mmm-hmm.

870
00:58:08,918 --> 00:58:10,647
If I could just tell her I'm sorry,

871
00:58:10,720 --> 00:58:15,054
that I'm, you know, I'm really sorry.

872
00:58:15,158 --> 00:58:17,854
And that I didn't mean
for any of this to happen.

873
00:58:17,927 --> 00:58:19,861
If she could just hear me say it,

874
00:58:19,929 --> 00:58:22,397
you know, just... Just hear my voice,

875
00:58:22,499 --> 00:58:25,730
(STAMMERING) she would
know how much I meant it.

876
00:58:27,570 --> 00:58:29,367
That is a very noble quest.

877
00:58:44,787 --> 00:58:47,187
ROSCURO: (STAMMERING) Your Highness?

878
00:58:50,126 --> 00:58:52,026
Your Highness?

879
00:58:53,129 --> 00:58:54,562
Is that you?

880
00:58:54,864 --> 00:58:56,229
My little mouse?

881
00:58:56,900 --> 00:58:58,800
Oh, I'm not a mouse. I...

882
00:58:59,269 --> 00:59:00,702
(STAMMERING) I'm a...

883
00:59:02,205 --> 00:59:03,229
Oh.

884
00:59:03,740 --> 00:59:04,866
I forgot.

885
00:59:05,141 --> 00:59:07,405
You're my little gentleman, aren't you?

886
00:59:10,480 --> 00:59:12,471
Have you come to tell me
how the story ends?

887
00:59:12,582 --> 00:59:14,277
Did you finish your quest?

888
00:59:15,485 --> 00:59:16,952
Where are you?

889
00:59:18,121 --> 00:59:20,089
I have come to apologize.

890
00:59:20,723 --> 00:59:23,248
Oh, you are noble, remember?

891
00:59:24,093 --> 00:59:26,254
You have nothing to be sorry about.

892
00:59:27,897 --> 00:59:29,330
Oh, but I am.

893
00:59:32,402 --> 00:59:33,835
I am sorry.

894
00:59:36,806 --> 00:59:38,740
(GASPING) I know you.

895
00:59:38,808 --> 00:59:41,299
- No, no.
- Oh, no!

896
00:59:41,411 --> 00:59:43,174
No! Please, please listen. Please.

897
00:59:43,279 --> 00:59:44,644
- A rat!
- Please. I just want to tell you.

898
00:59:44,747 --> 00:59:46,339
(SCREAMING) Someone, please!

899
00:59:46,449 --> 00:59:47,643
Listen. It's okay.

900
00:59:47,750 --> 00:59:50,150
Get it off me! There's a rat in my room!

901
00:59:50,486 --> 00:59:52,249
Please get him off!

902
00:59:52,322 --> 00:59:54,586
(SCREAMING)

903
00:59:57,994 --> 00:59:59,018
What?

904
01:00:00,663 --> 01:00:01,687
(PRINCESS PEA SHRIEKING)

905
01:00:04,867 --> 01:00:05,925
Rat!

906
01:00:06,469 --> 01:00:08,266
(PRINCESS PEA SHRIEKING)

907
01:00:08,371 --> 01:00:09,463
Oh!

908
01:00:10,773 --> 01:00:12,764
PRINCESS PEA: It's a rat!

909
01:00:19,849 --> 01:00:21,373
GUARD 1: Quick, rush him!

910
01:00:21,484 --> 01:00:22,542
GUARD 2: Get him!

911
01:00:22,652 --> 01:00:24,017
GUARD 3: Filthy rodent!

912
01:00:30,560 --> 01:00:31,618
Uh-oh.

913
01:00:32,996 --> 01:00:34,020
Oh!

914
01:00:39,235 --> 01:00:40,793
GUARD: Where'd he go?

915
01:00:48,878 --> 01:00:49,902
(GRUNTING)

916
01:00:51,881 --> 01:00:53,314
(PANTING)

917
01:01:21,744 --> 01:01:25,407
<i>NARRATOR: What would you do</i>
<i>if your own name was a bad word?</i>

918
01:01:27,550 --> 01:01:31,145
<i>If John or Beth or
Bill was an insult.</i>

919
01:01:32,689 --> 01:01:36,147
<i>Well, that's how Roscuro</i>
<i>came to feel about who he was.</i>

920
01:01:38,227 --> 01:01:42,220
<i>When your heart breaks,</i>
<i>it can grow back crooked.</i>

921
01:01:43,232 --> 01:01:46,998
<i>It grows back twisted
and gnarled and hard.</i>

922
01:01:49,338 --> 01:01:52,705
<i>Even as he changed,</i>
<i>Roscuro still had longing.</i>

923
01:01:53,743 --> 01:01:58,112
<i>But now he just longed for someone
whose heart was as hardened as his was.</i>

924
01:01:59,115 --> 01:02:04,678
Pretty princess.
Pretty, pretty princess pie.

925
01:02:05,755 --> 01:02:07,780
What a pretty princess!

926
01:02:09,425 --> 01:02:10,756
My gloves.

927
01:02:11,627 --> 01:02:12,855
My comb.

928
01:02:14,130 --> 01:02:16,860
My jewel-y, girly hat,

929
01:02:17,266 --> 01:02:21,600
all sitting on my princess head.

930
01:02:24,974 --> 01:02:30,310
Who's the pretty princess pumpkin pie?

931
01:02:33,282 --> 01:02:34,306
You are.

932
01:02:34,650 --> 01:02:37,278
Right. I am.

933
01:02:37,553 --> 01:02:41,284
You are. And you should be
dressed in those clothes.

934
01:02:41,958 --> 01:02:44,791
Quite right. I should.

935
01:02:44,994 --> 01:02:47,963
Mmm-hmm.
And you should lounge in that bed.

936
01:02:48,064 --> 01:02:49,326
Lounging.

937
01:02:49,432 --> 01:02:53,334
Lounging round, yes, the whole day!

938
01:02:53,736 --> 01:02:56,227
And you should be wearing that crown.

939
01:02:57,073 --> 01:02:58,665
I should be wearing a frown?

940
01:02:58,775 --> 01:03:02,472
No. No, no, no. Not a frown. A crown.

941
01:03:02,578 --> 01:03:05,775
Wow! Can't hear me own self think.

942
01:03:08,451 --> 01:03:09,679
- Ah!
- Shh!

943
01:03:09,786 --> 01:03:11,811
- Ah!
- Shh!

944
01:03:12,455 --> 01:03:13,513
Shh!

945
01:03:13,623 --> 01:03:15,352
- Ah!
- Shh!

946
01:03:17,126 --> 01:03:18,593
Who are you?

947
01:03:18,661 --> 01:03:20,253
I'm here to help you.

948
01:03:20,329 --> 01:03:22,923
I can't be caught with
a real rat in my bunk.

949
01:03:23,432 --> 01:03:25,093
I don't think so.

950
01:03:25,168 --> 01:03:26,192
(INHALES)

951
01:03:27,203 --> 01:03:29,763
And what if they find you
with a painting of the Princess?

952
01:03:29,839 --> 01:03:31,830
You think that's as bad as a rat?

953
01:03:32,608 --> 01:03:34,269
I want the same thing you do.

954
01:03:43,686 --> 01:03:45,176
(CLANKING)

955
01:03:46,189 --> 01:03:47,213
<i>Allo?</i>

956
01:03:49,659 --> 01:03:52,321
(BOTH EXCLAIMING)

957
01:03:52,395 --> 01:03:53,453
What are you doing?

958
01:03:53,696 --> 01:03:54,720
Uh...

959
01:03:55,665 --> 01:03:57,565
I need it for a baby.

960
01:03:59,468 --> 01:04:01,299
No, not a baby!

961
01:04:01,804 --> 01:04:02,828
For milady.

962
01:04:02,972 --> 01:04:05,736
(STAMMERING) I mean milady.

963
01:04:06,409 --> 01:04:07,501
Yes.

964
01:04:08,010 --> 01:04:09,238
To chop apples.

965
01:04:09,345 --> 01:04:10,369
Mmm.

966
01:04:10,479 --> 01:04:11,912
She'd like some apples.

967
01:04:14,550 --> 01:04:15,710
Now turn and leave.

968
01:04:15,818 --> 01:04:17,718
Now turn and leave.

969
01:04:20,223 --> 01:04:23,351
No, no! Just turn and leave.

970
01:04:23,559 --> 01:04:25,322
Oh, right. Sorry.

971
01:04:25,895 --> 01:04:26,919
Sorry. Bye.

972
01:04:27,029 --> 01:04:30,328
Oh, I can't hear you,
see, because deaf, but...

973
01:04:30,433 --> 01:04:31,491
A bit deaf.

974
01:04:34,670 --> 01:04:37,195
<i>NARRATOR: You know,
hurt is a funny thing.</i>

975
01:04:37,273 --> 01:04:41,869
<i>The same thing that makes one person angry</i>
<i>can put another person into grief.</i>

976
01:04:41,944 --> 01:04:44,674
Here, take care of me little princess.

977
01:04:44,947 --> 01:04:46,539
I can't no more.

978
01:04:46,782 --> 01:04:49,342
Oh, I will. Don't worry.

979
01:04:50,286 --> 01:04:51,344
(BABY COOING)

980
01:04:51,420 --> 01:04:52,512
I'm sorry.

981
01:04:53,222 --> 01:04:56,214
Sorry. So, so sorry!

982
01:04:59,395 --> 01:05:02,523
<i>NARRATOR: Gregory always said</i>
<i>that she had too much heart.</i>

983
01:05:02,598 --> 01:05:06,364
<i>And that's why they had to put</i>
<i>some of it on the outside.</i>

984
01:05:06,435 --> 01:05:07,868
<i>But let's face it.</i>

985
01:05:07,937 --> 01:05:10,599
<i>It's hard to see
something on your back.</i>

986
01:05:10,706 --> 01:05:14,802
<i>In fact, you can have a good heart</i>
<i>and not even know it.</i>

987
01:05:14,944 --> 01:05:16,707
You can do this. You know you can.

988
01:05:17,146 --> 01:05:18,374
I know I can.

989
01:05:18,447 --> 01:05:23,077
She belongs in the dungeon,
and you belong in the palace, like a princess.

990
01:05:24,620 --> 01:05:25,814
(CLATTERING)

991
01:05:28,758 --> 01:05:29,918
What are you doing?

992
01:05:31,227 --> 01:05:32,387
I'm cleaning, ma'am.

993
01:05:32,461 --> 01:05:33,485
(GROANS)

994
01:05:33,896 --> 01:05:35,227
With rope?

995
01:05:35,398 --> 01:05:36,422
It helps, ma'am.

996
01:05:36,499 --> 01:05:38,399
Well, stop it. You look ridiculous.

997
01:05:41,003 --> 01:05:42,129
Sorry, ma'am?

998
01:05:42,238 --> 01:05:44,798
I said you look ridiculous.

999
01:05:44,907 --> 01:05:48,172
<i>(ECHOING) Ridiculous,</i>
<i>ridiculous, ridiculous.</i>

1000
01:05:50,079 --> 01:05:51,740
- You can't do this, Mig.
- Gor.

1001
01:05:51,981 --> 01:05:53,608
Seems I am, ma'am.

1002
01:05:53,683 --> 01:05:55,150
You'll get in a terrible
amount of trouble.

1003
01:05:55,251 --> 01:05:57,242
Don't listen. You're the princess now.

1004
01:05:57,320 --> 01:05:58,810
I'm the princess now.

1005
01:05:58,921 --> 01:06:00,616
And you belong in the palace.

1006
01:06:00,690 --> 01:06:02,317
I belong in the palace.

1007
01:06:02,425 --> 01:06:03,483
And she belongs in...

1008
01:06:03,592 --> 01:06:05,583
PRINCESS PEA: No! You can't do this!

1009
01:06:05,661 --> 01:06:08,926
Help! Help! Someone help me!

1010
01:06:08,998 --> 01:06:10,966
Help! Help!

1011
01:06:11,767 --> 01:06:14,292
(FAINTLY) Help! Help!

1012
01:06:19,976 --> 01:06:22,035
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

1013
01:06:23,346 --> 01:06:25,177
PRINCESS PEA: Help! Help!

1014
01:06:27,149 --> 01:06:28,616
Help!

1015
01:06:29,518 --> 01:06:31,349
MIG: I'm in here!

1016
01:06:33,322 --> 01:06:34,812
Help!

1017
01:06:35,157 --> 01:06:37,022
You filthy, stinking rat!

1018
01:06:38,160 --> 01:06:39,627
You tricked me!

1019
01:06:39,895 --> 01:06:41,795
(RATS CLAMORING)

1020
01:06:42,565 --> 01:06:43,657
RAT 1: Here's the spot, rats!

1021
01:06:43,733 --> 01:06:45,132
